        "---\n",
        "title: \"Replication of Card and Krueger (1994)\"\n",
        "subtitle: \"Minimum Wages and Employment: A Case Study of the Fast-Food Industry in New Jersey and Pennsylvania\"\n",
        "author: \"Shuning Zhang\"\n",
        "date: 2026-04-21\n",
        "categories: [Causal Inference, Diff-in-Diff, Economics]\n",
        "format:\n",
        "  html:\n",
        "    toc: true\n",
        "    code-fold: true\n",
        "    page-layout: article\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Introduction\n",
        "\n",
        "Does raising the minimum wage cause unemployment? Standard economics textbooks say yes:\n",
        "if you force employers to pay workers more, they will simply hire fewer of them.\n",
        "Card and Krueger (1994) challenged this prediction head-on using a remarkably clean\n",
        "natural experiment.\n",
        "\n",
        "On April 1, 1992, New Jersey raised its minimum wage from \\$4.25 to \\$5.05 per hour —\n",
        "the highest state minimum wage in the country at the time. Pennsylvania, right next door,\n",
        "kept its minimum wage unchanged at \\$4.25. Card and Krueger surveyed 410 fast-food\n",
        "restaurants (Burger King, KFC, Roy Rogers, and Wendy's) in both states **before** the\n",
        "increase (February–March 1992) and **after** (November–December 1992).\n",
        "\n",
        "This setup is the classic **Difference-in-Differences (DiD)** design:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Treatment group**: New Jersey restaurants (subject to the wage increase)\n",
        "- **Control group**: Pennsylvania restaurants (no change)\n",
        "- **Key assumption**: Without the minimum wage increase, employment trends in both\n",
        "  states would have moved in parallel\n",
        "\n",
        "The DiD estimator subtracts two differences:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\hat{\\tau}_{DiD} = (\\bar{Y}_{NJ,after} - \\bar{Y}_{NJ,before}) - (\\bar{Y}_{PA,after} - \\bar{Y}_{PA,before})$$\n",
        "\n",
        "By comparing the *change* in NJ to the *change* in PA, we difference out any\n",
        "seasonal trends or macroeconomic shocks that affected both states equally — leaving\n",
        "only the effect of the minimum wage.\n",
        "\n",
        "Their headline finding: **employment in New Jersey did not fall** after the minimum wage\n",
        "increase. In fact, it rose slightly relative to Pennsylvania, directly contradicting\n",
        "the standard competitive model.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Main Analysis"
      ],
      "id": "af5baab6"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "message": false
