        "**What this shows:**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Before the increase (Wave 1), NJ and PA had nearly *identical* wage distributions —\n",
        "  about 30% of stores in both states paid exactly the old minimum of \\$4.25/hr.\n",
        "  This similarity supports the parallel-trends assumption underlying the DiD design.\n",
        "\n",
        "- After the increase (Wave 2), **85% of NJ stores** piled up right at the new \\$5.05\n",
        "  floor, while Pennsylvania's distribution barely moved. By Wave 2, *zero* NJ stores\n",
        "  still paid \\$4.25.\n",
        "\n",
        "- This dramatic shift is the \"first stage\" of the causal chain: the law actually changed\n",
        "  wages, so any subsequent employment effects can be attributed to the policy rather\n",
        "  than coincidence.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Despite this large wage shock, NJ employment *increased* relative to PA — the\n",
        "  central paradox that motivated the paper and challenged a generation of economists\n",
        "  to rethink the competitive model of the labor market.\n",
